  {
    "id": "How to Tell a Story_sem_0",
    "title": "STORIES EVOKE REFLECTION",
    "section": "STORIES EVOKE REFLECTION",
    "source": "How to Tell a Story",
    "text": "also inspired me to have an open mind as well as an open heart. I am again, just so grateful that your story reached me out here in the middle of nowhere to lift my spirit. <!-- BOUNDARY:CONTENT --> # STORIES EVOKE REFLECTION <span id=\"page-288-0\"></span>The smallest details in a story can conjure specific memories, shift your perspective entirely, or help you see another person's life in a revolutionary new light. Cheech Marin told a story about moving to Canada to avoid being drafted into the Vietnam War. When describing the final scene, the moment he saw his father for the first time after the war, a high-pitched sound escaped from his throat. After the show, an audience member told us that he burst into tears upon hearing this sound. He said the sound comes out when you tighten your larynx so you won't cry. He said that crying wasn't accepted in his household—and he makes the same sound.",
    "char_count": 904,
    "refiner_needed": false
  },
  {
    "id": "How to Tell a Story_sem_1",
    "title": "HOW NOT TO BREAK YOUR FUNNY BONE",
    "section": "<span id=\"page-132-1\"></span>HUMOR",
    "source": "How to Tell a Story",
    "text": "Don't take it personally! You may get tons of laughs and tons of tears, or you may be upstaged by a toddler who has decided at that exact moment she hates her tights. No matter what's going on, the subject of your toast is listening. Stay the course and share from the heart. What's most important is that your loved one feels celebrated and seen. <!-- BOUNDARY:CONTENT -->",
    "char_count": 373,
    "refiner_needed": false
  },
  {
    "id": "How to Tell a Story_sem_1",
    "title": "ABOUT THE AUTHORS",
    "section": "BRING HOW TO TELL A STORY TO YOUR BOOK CLUB!",
    "source": "How to Tell a Story",
    "text": "Her writing has appeared on *McSweeney's* and *The New Yorker*. Through it all, her love of storytelling runs deep because it gives her the phenomenal opportunity to laugh and cry with strangers. She was the intern that edited the podcast on GarageBand. Instagram: [@thekatetellers](http://instagram.com/thekatetellers) <!-- BOUNDARY:CONTENT -->",
    "char_count": 345,
    "refiner_needed": false
  },
  {
    "id": "How to Tell a Story_797f4f24",
    "title": "WHY \"THE MOTH\"?",
    "section": "WHY \"THE MOTH\"?",
    "source": "How to Tell a Story",
    "text": "Just to see.\" <span id=\"page-25-0\"></span>PEGI VAIL, FOUNDING BOARD MEMBER: We were all nervous as to how this first event would unfold, how the stories would be received, and if the format would work. It was appropriately titled \"Finding a Place.\" The stakes felt high that evening. We were reintroducing the idea of storytelling, stripped back to its bare bones.",
    "char_count": 364,
    "refiner_needed": false
  },
  {
    "id": "How to Tell a Story_sem_0",
    "title": "talking points for the host",
    "section": "<span id=\"page-343-0\"></span>HOW TO HOST A MOTH-STYLE STORYTELLING GATHERING",
    "source": "How to Tell a Story",
    "text": "ome the tellers up, picking their names at random, one at a time. The host might want to razzle-dazzle in a top hat or be a quieter presence who guides the night. Up to you! <!-- BOUNDARY:CONTENT --> #### talking points for the host - You provide the hat. Ask everyone who comes with a story to put their name in a hat. - Stories should be on time. Sticking to an allotted time frame is not only respectful to the listener, but also helps you focus and fine-tune your story. (At The Moth StorySLAM, we use a gentle whistle to remind folks at the five-minute mark that they should be wrapping up. If they keep going on and on, we whistle again. Pro tip: For the gripping stories, the time limit doesn't seem to matter at all. But for the long and meandering stories, the limit is really helpful.) - Stories should be true. There are no fact-checkers, but people can tell when stories veer into fiction. Moth listeners generously give tellers the benefit of the doubt—it is important to honor that faith! - Stories should stick to the theme. Tellers should stay on theme. (That said, if Aunt Pearl veers off to share a story of a torrid love affair during your Blunders-themed StorySLAM, will anyone really mind?) - Stories should be respectful. Stories that brazenly or casually glorify racism, sexism, ableism, or homophobia or make generalizations about other cultures destroy all the goodwill born from sharing stories. These negative elements kill the evening and leave lasting scars. So, NOPE. - Let the stories begin! But first, ask folks to turn off their phones. If you have a large group, you might want to clarify that you'll be picking only ten names from the hat because a night of fifteen stories is a loooong night. <!-- BOUNDARY:CONTENT -->",
    "char_count": 1754,
    "refiner_needed": false
  },
  {
    "id": "How to Tell a Story_50f77cf7",
